{"title_page": "Strangers (1978 TV series)", "text_new": "{{About|the 1978 ITV TV drama|the 2018 ITV TV drama|Strangers (2018 TV series)|the 2017 American web series|Strangers (2017 TV series)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Strangers\n| image                    = [[File:StrangersDVDBoxSet.jpg|250px]]\n| genre                    = [[Crime drama]]\n| based_on                 =\n| creator                  = [[Murray Smith (writer)|Murray Smith]]\n| writer                   =\n| director                 = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Don Henderson]]\n* Dennis Blanch \n* [[Frances Tomelty]]\n* [[John Ronane]] \n* [[David Hargreaves (actor)|David Hargreaves]] \n* [[Fiona Mollison]] \n* [[Mark McManus]] \n* [[Bruce Bould]] \n* [[Thorley Walters]] \n}}\n| composer                 = Mike Moran\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 5\n| num_episodes             = 32\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = Richard Everitt\n| producer                 = Mervyn Watson\n| cinematography           = Mike Thomson<br>Mike Popley\n| editor                   = David Rees\n| camera                   =\n| runtime                  = 60 minutes\n| company                  = [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]]\n| distributor              = [[ITV Studios]]\n| channel                  = [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] \n| picture_format           = [[4:3]]\n| audio_format             = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_aired              = {{start date|1978|6|5|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = {{end date|1982|10|20|df=yes}}\n| preceded_by              = ''[[The XYY Man]]''\n| followed_by              = ''[[Bulman]]''\n| website                  =\n}}\n\n'''''Strangers''''' is a British television [[crime drama]] series, principally written and created by [[Murray Smith (writer)|Murray Smith]], first broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] on 5 June 1978. The series, featuring the characters of Detective Sergeant [[George Bulman (fictional character)|George Bulman]] ([[Don Henderson]]) and his assistant Detective Constable Derek Willis (Dennis Blanch), was a spin-off from the 1976 TV series ''[[The XYY Man]]'', adapted from the novels of [[Kenneth Royce]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishdrama.org.uk/bulman.html|title=..: THE STRANGERS / THE XYY MAN / BULMAN :..|website=www.britishdrama.org.uk}}</ref> The series was first suggested by [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]] executives, who in 1977, outlined their plan to devise a new series to feature the regular characters of Bulman and Willis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediagems.de/01filmtv/bulman_engl.html|title=Strangers & Bulman|website=www.mediagems.de}}</ref>\n\nThe series began life as a fairly standard police drama, with Bulman positioned as its eccentric lead. The series' premise centred around a group of police officers, including Bulman and Willis, known as 'Unit 23', who are brought together from different parts of the country to [[Manchester]] to infiltrate areas and investigate crimes that familiar local detectives could not.<ref>https://www.memorabletv.com/tv/strangers-itv-1978-don-henderson/</ref> Five series were broadcast, with the final episode airing on 20 October 1982. Following the series, a further spin-off, simply entitled ''[[Bulman]]'', ran for two series on ITV. The series follows Bulman, again played by Don Henderson, as he continues to dabble in private detective work after retiring from the police force. All five series of ''Strangers'' were released on DVD via [[Network Distributing]] as a complete box set on 19 October 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Strangers-Complete-DVD-Don-Henderson/dp/B002KAIW3U/|title=Strangers - The Complete Series|date=19 October 2009|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nInitially, the 'Unit 23' team consisted of Bulman, Willis and WDC Linda Doran ([[Frances Tomelty]]). Their local liaison was provided by Detective Sergeant David Singer ([[John Ronane]]), while their superior officer was Detective Chief Inspector Rainbow ([[David Hargreaves (actor)|David Hargreaves]]). Despite being based around a comparatively small team of detectives, a regular feature of the programme in its early years was that few episodes featured the entire team, with most using just two or three of the regulars in any major role. The second series, shown in early 1979, introduced the character of WDC Vanessa Bennett, played by [[Fiona Mollison]], who replaced the outgoing Frances Tomelty. David Hargreaves would also depart the show following this series.\n\nFor the third series, Bulman, Willis, Bennett and the newly promoted Detective Inspector Singer became members of the 'Inner City Squad', under the command of Detective Chief Superintendent Jack Lambie ([[Mark McManus]]). The basic premise was similar, but rather than covering just the north west of England, the team's remit now extended to the whole country. By the fourth series, Bulman had also gained promotion to Detective Chief Inspector. This series also re-introduced the semi-regular character of William 'Bill' Dugdale ([[Thorley Walters]]), a member of the British [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] and [[Secret Intelligence Service|Secret Service]]s who would become involved when there was a political or intelligence aspect to the investigation. His role was not necessarily to help the detectives; that would only happen when it was in the government's interest for them to succeed.\n\n==Production==\nThe first series was shot primarily on videotape, with only location footage shot on film. The second series would feature even more film, with the opening episode ''The Wheeler Dealers'' being shot entirely on film, and the final episode, ''Marriages, Deaths And Births'', being shot entirely on film bar the title sequence and a small number of scenes at the police station. From the third series onwards, the entire production moved to 16mm film. \n\nThe first series incorporated a number of writers, with only [[Leslie Duxbury]] writing more than one episode. He would later contribute one further script for the second series. During series two, series creator \n[[Murray Smith (writer)|Murray Smith]] came to the fore as the principal writer, having only previously scripted one episode for the first series. Smith went on to write all but six of the remaining twenty-five episodes.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Don Henderson]] as DS/DCI [[George Bulman (fictional character)|George Bulman]]\n* Dennis Blanch as DC/DS Derek Willis\n* [[Frances Tomelty]] as WDC Linda Doran (Series 1\u20142)\n* [[John Ronane]] as DS/DI David Singer (Series 1\u20144)\n* [[David Hargreaves (actor)|David Hargreaves]] as DCI Rainbow (Series 1\u20142)\n* [[Fiona Mollison]] as WDC Vanessa Bennett (Series 2\u20145)\n* [[Mark McManus]] as DCS Jack Lambie (Series 3\u20145)\n* [[Bruce Bould]] as DI Tom Casey (Series 3)\n* [[Thorley Walters]] as William 'Bill' Dugdale (Series 3\u20145)\n\n==Episodes==\n===Series 1 (1978)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\"\n! style=\"background:#D48142;\"| Episode\n! style=\"background:#D48142;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#D48142;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#D48142;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#D48142;\"| Original airdate\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber= 1\n | Title= The Paradise Set\n | Aux1= Murray Smith\n | Aux2= Carole Wilks\n | OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|1978|6|5|df=y}}\n | ShortSummary= Arriving in Manchester to work on their new patch as 'strangers' to the local underworld, Bulman and Willis investigate a jewel robbery.\n | LineColor= D48142\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber= 2\n | Title= Duty Roster\n | Aux1= Ivor Marshall\n | Aux2= Oliver Horsburgh\n | OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|1